Answer:
Your first and second cases are equivalent. You need to understand complex numbers to be able to see that. The complex numbers, written C\mathbb{C} are of the form x+iyx+iy where xx and yy are real numbers that you already know and ii is a special number with i2=âˆ’1i^2 = -1. Usually, we have i=âˆšâˆ’1i = \sqrt{-1}. To see that the second case is the same as the first, notice that:

2x+3(xâˆ’1)(x2+4)â‰¡Axâˆ’1+Bxâˆ’2i+Cx+2i\frac{2x+3}{(x-1)(x^2+4)} \equiv \frac{A}{x-1}+\frac{B}{x-2i}+\frac{C}{x+2i}

where A=1A=1, B=âˆ’12âˆ’i14B=-\frac{1}{2}-i\frac{1}{4} and C=âˆ’12+i14C=-\frac{1}{2}+i\frac{1}{4}. The only reason you are taught the second form is that you don't know about xÂ±2ix\pm 2i and they recombine them:

Bxâˆ’2i+Cx+2iâ‰¡1âˆ’xx2+4\frac{B}{x-2i} + \frac{C}{x+2i} \equiv \frac{1-x}{x^2+4}

The third case isn't quite the same. But notice that the denominator is a cubic. When you multiply it out, you'll have an x3x^3 and lower powers. We couldn't get away with just two fraction because

Axâˆ’a+Bxâˆ’bâ‰¡A(xâˆ’b)+B(xâˆ’a)(xâˆ’a)(xâˆ’b)\frac{A}{x-a}+\frac{B}{x-b} \equiv \frac{A(x-b)+B(x-a)}{(x-a)(x-b)}

and this only has a quadratic expression as the denominator.

We can split this into two integrals. Both integrals will be from x=0 to x=1. However, one integral will be from y=0 to y=x^2 and the other will be from y=x^2 to y=1. We can see the first integral is where y<x^2 so we should have x^2-y as our integrand. Similarly, our second integral represents the region where y > x^2 so our integrand will be y-x^2. We can now write this out and it becomes much simpler to solve:
\int\int_R |y-x^2| dydx = \int_0^1\int_0^{x^2} (x^2-y) dydx + \int_0^1\int_{x^2}^1 (y-x^2)dydx
= \int_0^1 \left(x^2y - \frac{y^2}{2}\right)^{y=x^2}_{y=0} dx + \int_0^1\left(\frac{y^2}{2} - x^2y\right)_{y=x^2}^{y=1} dx
= \int_0^1  \left(x^4-\frac{x^4}{2}\right) dx + \int_0^1 \left(\frac{1}{2} - x^2 - \frac{x^4}{2} + x^4 \right) dx
Because these integrals are over the same region, with respect to the same variable we can combine them and get:
= \int_0^1 x^4 - x^2 + \frac{1}{2}
= \left( \frac{x^5}{5} - \frac{x^3}{3} + \frac{x}{2} \right)_{x=0}^{x=1}
= \frac{1}{5} - \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{2} = \frac{11}{30}

The expression for t should be (possibly a mistake in the partial fraction decomposition) t =\frac{500}{140}\ln \left|v+70\right|-\frac{500}{140}\ln \left|v-70\right|+C

Using that \ln(x)-\ln(y)=\ln(x/y) we get t-C=\dfrac{500}{140}\ln\left(\dfrac{|v+70|}{|v-70|}\right)\implies e^{\frac{140}{500}(t-C)}=\dfrac{|v+70|}{|v-70|}

From the initial condition t=0, v=0 we find C=0.

As v=0 in some neighbourhood \dfrac{|v+70|}{|v-70|}=\dfrac{70+v}{70-v}. We can now express v in terms of t:

e^{\frac{140}{500}t}=\dfrac{70+v}{70-v}\implies v(e^{\frac{140}{500}t}+1)=70(e^{\frac{140}{500}t}-1)\implies v=\dfrac{70(e^{\frac{140}{500}t}-1)}{1+e^{\frac{140}{500}t}}=\dfrac{70(e^{\frac{7}{25}t}-1)}{1+e^{\frac{7}{25}t}}

It is now obvious that \displaystyle\lim_{t\to\infty} v(t)=70.

